0. Stack Selection and Profile Completion
0.1 Current status
This document is currently a template. It becomes the authoritative technical realization document only after stack selection is complete and the profile is fully instantiated and approved.
0.2 Technology decisions required before profile completion
The following decisions must be made before this profile can be finalized:
1. Frontend framework and rendering posture
2. CMS or content platform
3. Backend or orchestration pattern, if needed
4. Hosting and deployment platform
5. Storage or persistence posture
6. Validation, testing, and build tooling
7. Preview, publishing, and lifecycle handling approach
8. Secrets and environment-configuration approach
0.3 Selection criteria
Technology choices must be evaluated against the governed system rather than by generic popularity alone. Use the following criteria:
1. Fit to the Website Specification requirements
2. Fit to the Website Solution Architecture Standard
3. Fit to the Website Realization and Page Composition Standard
4. Support for CMS-managed page instances and approved variation
5. Support for generated detail-page behavior
6. Support for governed configuration resolution
7. Support for boundary preservation and runtime contracts
8. Developer usability and maintainability for a lean team
9. Compatibility with controlled code-generation workflows
10. Operational simplicity and reliability
0.4 Decision questions by technology area
For the frontend, decide: What framework best supports governed page composition, reusable component realization, strong typing, metadata handling, and maintainable rendering boundaries?
For the CMS, decide: Which CMS best supports the required content types, global settings, page-instance handling, generated detail pages, preview, publishing, and workflow behavior?
For backend or orchestration, decide: Is a BFF, orchestration service, or equivalent runtime layer required, or can the implementation remain simpler without violating governed boundaries?
For hosting and deployment, decide: Which platform best supports the required delivery posture, environment separation, secrets management, preview flow, and rollout discipline?
For persistence, decide: What must be persisted outside CMS content, and where should those records live without blurring governed content and configuration boundaries?
For tooling, decide: Which validation, testing, linting, typing, and build tools are appropriate for the chosen stack and team capability?
0.5 Recommended working sequence
1. Confirm the Website Specification and active Site Configuration Record are stable enough for technical selection.
2. Choose the CMS and frontend, because those two choices drive most downstream realization decisions.
3. Decide whether a separate backend or orchestration layer is needed.
4. Choose hosting, persistence, and tooling.
5. Instantiate the selected-technology sections of the Technical Build Profile with concrete technical decisions.
6. Complete implementation rules, code-generation rules, codebase and delivery model, and conformance expectations.
7. Review the full instantiated Technical Build Profile against the upstream artifacts before baselining it.
0.6 Supersession note
Once complete, this document supersedes all separate stack-selection guidance and becomes the primary technical reference for implementation.
1. Purpose, Scope, Role, and Authority
1.1 Purpose
This document defines the stack-specific technical realization profile for one governed website solution.
Its purpose is to translate the governed artifact stack into a concrete technical implementation model so that implementation is repeatable, structural intent is preserved, page realization is controlled, CMS behavior is realized within governed boundaries, configuration behavior is technically enforced, code-generation tools operate within explicit limits, and conformance can be assessed against a defined technical target.
1.2 Scope
This document is in scope for the selected technical stack for this implementation; technical realization mappings from governing artifacts; logical module to technical realization mapping; buildable module, reusable component, page type, page instance, and page composition realization; CMS technical realization; runtime configuration realization; technical interfaces and runtime contracts; implementation rules; code-generation operating rules; codebase, environment, and delivery model; and technical conformance expectations.
1.3 Out of Scope
This document does not define or redefine product requirements for the website, governed configuration semantics, logical module meaning at the structural architecture level, buildable module meaning at the realization standard level, or page-type and page-composition semantics at the realization standard level. Those are defined by the upstream governing artifacts.
1.4 Relationship to Upstream Artifacts
This document derives from the Website Solution System Framework, Website Specification, Site Configuration Standard, Site Configuration Record, Website Solution Architecture Standard, and Website Realization and Page Composition Standard.
    This document must realize those artifacts and must not silently contradict, expand, weaken, or redefine them.
1.5 Authority
This document is authoritative only for stack-specific technical realization within its declared scope. It governs the selected technical stack for this implementation, where technical responsibilities live, which technical boundaries must be preserved, how governed modules, pages, configuration, and CMS behavior are technically realized, and what developers and code-generation tools may and may not do in implementation.
