5. Buildable Module, Component, and Page Realization
5.1 Buildable Module Realization Pattern
Each buildable module must be implemented as a clearly bounded technical unit that realizes one governed functional responsibility, receives only its approved inputs, produces only its approved outputs, and does not silently absorb page-level ownership.
Buildable modules may be realized as site-frame units, page-body feature units, support module implementations, or other approved realization forms consistent with the upstream standards.
5.2 Reusable Component Realization Pattern
Reusable components must be implemented as smaller reusable building parts that are composable inside approved modules, do not redefine module meaning, do not own page composition, and do not bypass configuration or data boundaries.
5.3 Page Type Realization Pattern
Each page type must have a clear technical representation that defines the page class, required and optional module patterns, page-level concerns, permitted CMS-managed variation, and composition ownership.
5.4 Page Instance Realization Pattern
A page instance must be technically realized as a managed page record or generated page resolution result that conforms to one governed page type, binds approved content and metadata, receives approved configuration inputs, and participates in governed page composition.
5.5 Page Composition Realization Pattern
Page composition must be technically realized through an approved composition mechanism.
That mechanism must assemble approved buildable modules, enforce ordering, repeatability, and prohibition rules, preserve page-level ownership, and prevent modules from self-owning page structure merely because they are visually dominant.
6. CMS Realization Model
6.1 CMS Content Types and Records
This profile must define the technical realization of content types, shared or global settings records, generated-page source entries, and any approved supporting records such as submissions or workflow records.
6.2 CMS Page-Instance Handling
This profile must define how page instances are created or resolved, which page instances are CMS-managed directly, which page instances are generated from entries, and how page metadata and approved page-level settings are managed.
6.3 Generated Page Behavior
This profile must define how generated pages are technically realized from CMS entries and how those generated pages remain aligned to governed page types and composition rules.
6.4 Global Settings Realization
This profile must define how global settings and shared content are stored, retrieved, validated, and injected into the runtime system.
6.5 Preview, Publishing, and Lifecycle Behavior
This profile must define preview behavior, publishing behavior, lifecycle-state handling, and boundaries between editor-managed and fixed technical behavior.
6.6 Editor-Managed Versus Fixed Technical Boundaries
This profile must explicitly state what the CMS is technically allowed to vary, what is fixed by upstream standards, and what must not be overridden by editor-facing controls.
7. Runtime Configuration and Technical Contracts
7.1 Source of Truth for Active Configuration
The source of truth for active governed configuration must be explicit. It must resolve to the active Site Configuration Record or its approved technical representation.
7.2 Resolution Path
The configuration resolution path must define where configuration is loaded from, how it is validated, how it is shaped for runtime use, and how consumers receive it.
7.3 Injection Strategy
The injection strategy must define where resolved configuration enters runtime flow, how it becomes available to page composition, rendering, and interaction layers, and where injection is prohibited.
7.4 Consumer Boundaries
The technical profile must define which consumers may access raw configuration records, resolved configuration objects, and presentation-ready configuration values. Unauthorized local consumption paths are not allowed.
7.5 CMS Adapter Contracts
The CMS adapter contracts must define approved CMS access interfaces, expected response shapes, validation expectations, error behavior, and caching behavior where approved.
7.6 Configuration Resolution Contracts
These contracts must define resolved output shapes, required fields, optional fields, approved fallback behavior, and error behavior for invalid or missing governed values.
7.7 Page Composition Inputs and Outputs
Page composition must define its technical contracts for page type, page instance, normalized content inputs, resolved configuration inputs, route context inputs, and composed page output or presentation model.
7.8 View-Model or Presentation-Model Contracts
Where view-model or presentation-model shaping is used, the contract must define approved input sources, expected output shape, validation boundaries, and prohibited direct rendering access to raw upstream data shapes.
7.9 Validation Boundaries
Runtime validation must occur at explicitly defined boundaries such as CMS adapter outputs, configuration resolution outputs, page composition inputs, inquiry or interaction inputs, and other critical contract surfaces.
7.10 Permitted Interface Dependencies
The profile must define the permitted dependency directions between CMS adapters, normalization, configuration resolution, page composition, rendering, interaction handling, and metadata handling.
7.11 Prohibited Bypasses
The profile must explicitly prohibit direct raw CMS access from rendering layers, local configuration resolution in unauthorized consumers, hidden page composition logic inside modules, bypass of runtime validation at approved contract boundaries, and direct interface shortcuts that violate the governed technical mapping.
7.12 Failure and Error Boundary Rules
This profile must define how the system behaves when CMS adapter responses are invalid or incomplete, configuration resolution fails, required page-composition inputs are missing, a buildable module contract is not satisfied, runtime validation fails, or a required page instance cannot be resolved.
This profile must also define which failures fail closed, which may use governed fallback behavior, which layer owns each class of failure, which conditions must raise explicit error states rather than silently degrading, and which failures may surface as safe fallback UI and which must stop rendering or publishing.
8. Implementation and Code-Generation Rules
8.1 No Local Invention of Structural Constructs
Implementation must not invent new logical modules, new buildable module categories, new page-type meanings, or new composition semantics outside governed change.
8.2 No Bypass of Governed Configuration
Implementation must not bypass the approved configuration resolution path.
8.3 No Direct Raw CMS Usage Outside Approved Layers
Raw CMS access must remain inside approved content-access and adapter layers.
8.4 No Page Composition Logic Inside Modules Unless Explicitly Allowed
Page composition ownership must remain in approved composition mechanisms.
8.5 No Redefinition of Page-Type or Module Meaning in Code
Implementation may realize governed constructs but may not redefine their meaning.
8.6 No Unauthorized Business-Logic Decisions in Rendering Layers
Rendering layers must not absorb logic beyond approved presentation scope.
8.7 What Code-Generation Tools May Do
Code-generation tools may generate implementation conforming to the approved artifacts, realize existing modules, components, and contracts, refactor within governed boundaries where explicitly allowed, and generate tests and validation scaffolding where required.
8.8 What Code-Generation Tools Must Not Do
Code-generation tools must not invent new structural constructs, invent new configuration pathways, redefine page composition behavior, bypass runtime validation or governed contracts, or silently reinterpret governed terms or meanings.
8.9 Required Input Artifacts
Code generation must not proceed without the required governing inputs appropriate to the task, which may include the Website Specification, Site Configuration Standard, Site Configuration Record, Website Solution Architecture Standard, Website Realization and Page Composition Standard, and this Technical Build Profile.
8.10 Review and Acceptance Requirements
Generated implementation must be reviewed against scope of the requested change, conformance to upstream artifacts, conformance to this technical profile, contract integrity, and prohibited-bypass rules.
8.11 Regeneration and Change Rules
Regenerated outputs and technical changes must preserve governed boundaries and must not silently introduce structural or runtime drift.
9. Codebase, Environment, and Delivery Model
9.1 Codebase Structure
The codebase structure must be explicit and must support preservation of governed boundaries, traceability from governed constructs to implementation units, and maintainable separation of runtime responsibilities.
9.2 Package / Service Organization
If the implementation uses multiple packages, libraries, services, handlers, or apps, their responsibilities and relationships must be explicit.
9.3 Environment Model
The environment model must define local development, test, staging, and production. Environment behavior must preserve configuration discipline and functional parity at the level required for reliable delivery.
9.4 CI/CD Model
The delivery pipeline must be explicit and must define build behavior, validation gates, test execution, deployment triggers, and release control.
9.5 Validation and Testing Gates
This profile must define required automated gates such as type checking, linting, unit tests where required, integration tests where required, runtime contract validation where required, and build validation.
9.6 Deployment Model
This profile must define deployment target, release flow, rollback or recovery posture where required, and preview or staged release behavior if used.
9.7 Secrets and Configuration Management
This profile must define how secrets are stored and injected, how environment-specific configuration is handled, how governed configuration is distinguished from deployment and environment configuration, and prohibited secret/config handling behaviors.
10. Conformance Model
10.1 What Is Checked
Technical conformance checks must cover realization mapping integrity, logical module boundary preservation, buildable module and component realization integrity, CMS boundary preservation, configuration boundary preservation, runtime contract preservation, and code-generation rule compliance.
10.2 Who Checks It
Conformance must be checked by the document owner or delegated governance owner for the technical realization domain.
10.3 When It Is Checked
Conformance must be checked when the initial implementation profile is created, a materially revised technical profile is proposed, a significant stack change is proposed, a major generated implementation change is proposed, or a governed exception is requested.
10.4 Non-Conformance Handling
Technical realization that materially violates this profile must not be treated as accepted until the non-conformance is resolved or explicitly authorized as a governed exception.
10.5 Exception Handling
Any technical exception must declare the rule being exceeded or bypassed, the reason, the scope, the impact, the approval path, and the duration if temporary.
